{
  "executive_summary": "A two-track ML pipeline architecture: a lightweight online serving path optimized for sub-100ms P99 inference during checkout, and an offline batch training path for weekly model retraining. The system uses a model registry with versioned artifacts and a traffic-splitting gateway to enable instant rollback. Feature computation is split into pre-computed (batch) and real-time (point-of-lookup) to meet latency requirements. Designed for a 4-person team — simplicity is the dominant constraint.",

  "architecture": {
    "components": [
      {
        "name": "Feature Store",
        "responsibility": "Pre-computes and serves features. Batch features (zone historical averages, courier reliability scores) are computed offline and written to a low-latency key-value store. Real-time features (current courier load, weather) are fetched at inference time from upstream services and cached with short TTLs.",
        "boundaries": "Owns the canonical feature definitions and transformations. Both training and serving pipelines read from this component, eliminating training-serving skew."
      },
      {
        "name": "Model Training Pipeline",
        "responsibility": "Weekly batch job that pulls labeled delivery data (order → actual delivery time), joins with feature snapshots, trains a gradient-boosted tree model (XGBoost/LightGBM), evaluates against holdout set, and publishes versioned artifact to Model Registry.",
        "boundaries": "Runs offline. Has no path to production serving except through the Model Registry gate. Owns training data validation, feature engineering logic (shared with Feature Store via versioned transform code), and evaluation metrics."
      },
      {
        "name": "Model Registry",
        "responsibility": "Versioned store for model artifacts, metadata (training metrics, data lineage, feature schema version), and deployment state (which version is 'active', which is 'canary', which is 'previous').",
        "boundaries": "Single source of truth for model lifecycle. Serving layer reads deployment state from here. Rollback is a metadata update — swap 'active' pointer to 'previous' version."
      },
      {
        "name": "Prediction Service",
        "responsibility": "Stateless HTTP/gRPC service that loads the active model into memory, assembles features from Feature Store, runs inference, and returns predicted delivery time. Horizontally scalable.",
        "boundaries": "Owns inference latency SLA (100ms P99). Does NOT own model selection logic — reads active model version from Registry on startup and via periodic poll (or push notification). Model is loaded in-process for zero-network-hop inference."
      },
      {
        "name": "Traffic Router / Shadow Gateway",
        "responsibility": "Sits in front of Prediction Service instances. Routes traffic between active model and canary model during rollout. Enables A/B testing and shadow-mode evaluation of new models before promotion.",
        "boundaries": "Thin routing layer only — no business logic. Can be as simple as a weighted load balancer config or feature flag."
      },
      {
        "name": "Monitoring & Evaluation Service",
        "responsibility": "Tracks prediction accuracy (predicted vs actual delivery time), model drift metrics, latency percentiles, and error rates. Triggers alerts when accuracy degrades beyond threshold. Feeds back into rollback decisions.",
        "boundaries": "Read-only consumer of prediction logs and delivery outcome events. Does not modify model state directly — alerts humans or triggers automated rollback via Registry API."
      },
      {
        "name": "Delivery Data Lake",
        "responsibility": "Append-only store of historical delivery records: order details, features at prediction time, predicted time, actual delivery time. Source of truth for training data.",
        "boundaries": "Ingests from operational systems. Training pipeline reads from here. Monitoring service writes prediction-vs-actual pairs here."
      }
    ],
    "interfaces": [
      {
        "from": "Checkout Service (external)",
        "to": "Prediction Service",
        "contract": "POST /predict {weight, distance, zone, time_of_day, weather_code, courier_id} → {predicted_minutes, confidence_interval, model_version}",
        "coupling_type": "synchronous, request-response, latency-critical"
      },
      {
        "from": "Prediction Service",
        "to": "Feature Store",
        "contract": "GET features by (zone, courier_id, time_window) → pre-computed feature vector. Must respond in <20ms.",
        "coupling_type": "synchronous, low-latency lookup (Redis/DynamoDB)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Prediction Service",
        "to": "Model Registry",
        "contract": "Poll or subscribe for active model version. On change, download artifact and hot-reload. Startup: block until model loaded.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous, event-driven or polling (non-critical path)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Model Training Pipeline",
        "to": "Model Registry",
        "contract": "PUT /models/{version} with artifact binary, metrics JSON, feature schema hash. Registry validates schema compatibility.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous, batch (weekly)"
      },
      {
        "from": "Model Training Pipeline",
        "to": "Delivery Data Lake",
        "contract": "Read partitioned delivery records for training window (e.g., last 90 days). SQL or Spark read interface.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous, batch read"
      },
      {
        "from": "Monitoring & Evaluation Service",
        "to": "Model Registry",
        "contract": "POST /models/{version}/rollback — triggers pointer swap from current active to previous version.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous, event-triggered"
      },
      {
        "from": "Prediction Service",
        "to": "Monitoring & Evaluation Service",
        "contract": "Async emit of prediction events: {request_id, model_version, features, prediction, timestamp}. Fire-and-forget to message queue.",
        "coupling_type": "asynchronous, fire-and-forget (Kafka/SQS)"
      }
    ],
    "data_flow": "Checkout request → Prediction Service assembles feature vector (20ms budget: batch features from Feature Store KV lookup + real-time features from request payload) → in-process model inference (10-30ms for tree model) → response with prediction + model version. Asynchronously: prediction event emitted to queue → Monitoring service joins with actual delivery time (when available) → drift detection. Weekly: Data Lake → Training Pipeline → new model artifact → Registry → Prediction Service hot-reloads.",
    "patterns_used": [
      {
        "pattern": "Feature Store (dual-mode: batch + real-time)",
        "rationale": "Eliminates training-serving skew — the #1 cause of silent ML degradation in production. Both pipelines consume identical feature definitions. Batch features are pre-computed to stay within latency budget."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Model Registry with version pointers",
        "rationale": "Decouples training from serving. Rollback is O(1) — a pointer swap, not a redeployment. Enables audit trail of every model that touched production."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "In-process inference (embedded model)",
        "rationale": "Tree-based models (XGBoost/LightGBM) are small enough to load into service memory. Eliminates network hop to a separate model server, saving 20-50ms — critical for the 100ms P99 budget."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Shadow/Canary deployment for models",
        "rationale": "New models are evaluated in shadow mode (receives real traffic, predictions logged but not returned) or canary mode (small % of traffic) before full promotion. Catches regressions before they affect all users."
      },
      {
        "pattern": "Async prediction logging",
        "rationale": "Prediction events are emitted fire-and-forget so monitoring never adds latency to the critical serving path."
      }
    ]
  },

  "domain_model": {
    "bounded_contexts": [
      {
        "name": "Delivery Prediction (Core)",
        "classification": "core",
        "aggregates": ["PredictionRequest (value object: features + response)", "ModelVersion (entity: artifact, metrics, deployment state, feature schema)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Model Lifecycle (Supporting)",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["TrainingRun (entity: data snapshot, hyperparams, evaluation results)", "ModelArtifact (entity: versioned binary + metadata)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Feature Engineering (Supporting)",
        "classification": "supporting",
        "aggregates": ["FeatureDefinition (entity: name, transform logic, version)", "FeatureSnapshot (value object: materialized features at a point in time)"]
      },
      {
        "name": "Delivery Operations (External/Generic)",
        "classification": "generic",
        "aggregates": ["DeliveryRecord (entity: order, courier, timestamps — owned by operational system, consumed read-only)"]
      }
    ],
    "context_map": [
      {
        "upstream": "Delivery Operations",
        "downstream": "Model Lifecycle",
        "relationship": "Conformist — training pipeline conforms to the delivery data schema as-is, with an ACL for data cleaning/validation"
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Feature Engineering",
        "downstream": "Delivery Prediction",
        "relationship": "Shared Kernel — feature definitions are shared code between training and serving to prevent skew"
      },
      {
        "upstream": "Model Lifecycle",
        "downstream": "Delivery Prediction",
        "relationship": "Customer-Supplier — training publishes models, serving consumes them via Registry contract"
      }
    ]
  },

  "trade_offs": [
    {
      "decision": "In-process tree model (XGBoost/LightGBM) over deep learning or external model server",
      "gains": "Deterministic low-latency inference (<30ms). Simple deployment — model is a file loaded at startup. No GPU infrastructure needed. 4-person team can operate this.",
      "sacrifices": "Potentially lower accuracy ceiling vs deep learning. Cannot serve models that exceed process memory. Less flexibility for multi-model ensemble.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["TensorFlow Serving / Triton for GPU inference — rejected: adds infrastructure complexity, network hop, GPU cost; not justified for tabular regression", "Real-time deep learning model — rejected: latency risk at P99, requires GPU fleet, team too small to operate"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Weekly batch retraining over online/continuous learning",
      "gains": "Simple, auditable, debuggable. Each training run is reproducible. Rollback is straightforward. Matches team capacity.",
      "sacrifices": "Model may be stale for up to 7 days if delivery patterns shift rapidly (e.g., holiday surge). Not adaptive to sudden distribution shifts.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Continuous online learning — rejected: hard to debug, hard to rollback, introduces training-serving coupling, team too small", "Daily retraining — viable future evolution if weekly proves insufficient"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Redis/DynamoDB for feature serving over a full-featured feature platform (Feast, Tecton)",
      "gains": "Minimal infrastructure. Team already knows KV stores. Feature definitions live in code — versioned, reviewed, tested.",
      "sacrifices": "No built-in feature lineage UI, no point-in-time join automation. Manual effort to maintain training-serving parity.",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Feast — viable if team grows; adds operational overhead for 4 people", "Tecton — overkill for current scale and team size"]
    },
    {
      "decision": "Pointer-swap rollback over blue-green model deployments",
      "gains": "Instant rollback (seconds). No need to maintain two full serving fleets. Previous model artifact stays in registry.",
      "sacrifices": "Brief inconsistency window during hot-reload across instances (mitigated by health checks).",
      "alternatives_considered": ["Blue-green deployment with two service fleets — rejected: doubles infrastructure cost for a scenario that should be rare"]
    }
  ],

  "flexibility_points": [
    {
      "area": "Model algorithm",
      "evolution_path": "The in-process inference pattern supports any model that can be serialized to a file and loaded into memory. Can swap XGBoost → LightGBM → CatBoost → even a small neural net without changing serving infrastructure."
    },
    {
      "area": "Retraining cadence",
      "evolution_path": "Weekly is a scheduling config. Can move to daily or triggered-on-data-volume by changing the cron trigger. Pipeline logic stays the same."
    },
    {
      "area": "Feature set",
      "evolution_path": "Adding new features requires: (1) add to feature definition code, (2) backfill in data lake, (3) retrain. No serving infrastructure changes needed — feature vector size is dynamic."
    },
    {
      "area": "Multi-model routing",
      "evolution_path": "Traffic Router can evolve from simple active/canary to zone-specific models (e.g., urban vs rural) or time-of-day models by extending routing rules."
    }
  ],

  "rigidity_points": [
    {
      "area": "100ms P99 latency budget",
      "reason": "This constrains the entire serving architecture: in-process inference, pre-computed features, no chained service calls. Any change that adds latency (larger model, external feature lookups, ensemble) must be validated against this hard constraint."
    },
    {
      "area": "Feature Store as shared kernel between training and serving",
      "reason": "Intentionally rigid — training-serving skew is the most common and hardest-to-debug failure mode in ML systems. Feature transform code MUST be shared, versioned, and tested together."
    },
    {
      "area": "Model Registry as the single gate to production",
      "reason": "No model reaches serving without passing through the registry. This is a deliberate chokepoint for safety — it enforces evaluation, versioning, and rollback capability."
    }
  ],

  "risks": [
    {
      "risk": "Training-serving skew despite shared feature code — subtle differences in data types, null handling, or feature computation timing between batch training and real-time serving",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Integration test that runs inference on a known dataset through the full serving path and compares predictions to offline evaluation. Run this test before every model promotion. Log feature vectors at serving time and compare distributions to training data."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Feature Store latency spike (Redis/DynamoDB) blows the 100ms budget",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Set aggressive timeouts (20ms) on feature lookups. Implement fallback: if feature store is slow, use default/cached feature values and flag the prediction as degraded. Monitor P99 of feature lookups separately."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Model accuracy degrades silently — predictions are wrong but no immediate signal (actual delivery time is only known 30-90 minutes later)",
      "severity": "high",
      "mitigation": "Monitor prediction distribution shift in real-time (if predicted times suddenly cluster differently, alert). Async join of predictions with actuals and alert on MAE/MAPE threshold breach. Automated rollback trigger if error exceeds threshold for N consecutive hours."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Cold start on deployment — new service instances need to download model + warm feature cache before serving",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Health check gate: instance reports unhealthy until model is loaded and feature cache is warm. Pre-bake model into container image or use init container to download before readiness probe passes."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Team bus factor — 2 ML engineers owning training + feature engineering, 2 platform engineers owning serving + infrastructure, knowledge silos form",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Pair across tracks on model deployment and rollback procedures. Document the Model Registry contract and promotion process. Runbooks for rollback (should be a single CLI command)."
    },
    {
      "risk": "Data quality regression in delivery records corrupts training data",
      "severity": "medium",
      "mitigation": "Data validation step in training pipeline: check for schema violations, null rates, outlier delivery times (e.g., >24 hours), sudden volume drops. Fail training run loudly if validation fails."
    }
  ],

  "implementation_guidance": {
    "recommended_approach": "Phase 1 (Weeks 1-3): Build the serving path end-to-end with a simple heuristic model (distance/speed lookup) to validate the latency budget and feature serving infrastructure. Phase 2 (Weeks 3-5): Build the training pipeline and Model Registry; train first real model and deploy through the registry. Phase 3 (Weeks 5-7): Add monitoring, canary deployment, and automated rollback. This sequence gets a working (if naive) prediction into checkout fast, then iterates on model quality — the hardest-to-debug issues are always in the serving path, not the model.",
    "files_to_create_or_modify": [
      "prediction-service/ — Stateless HTTP service (Python FastAPI or Go for latency), loads model in-process",
      "feature-store/ — Shared feature definition library (Python package), used by both training and serving",
      "training-pipeline/ — Weekly batch job (Python, Airflow/Prefect DAG), reads from data lake, trains model, publishes to registry",
      "model-registry/ — Can start with S3 + DynamoDB metadata table, or MLflow if team prefers",
      "monitoring/ — Prediction logger (async queue consumer), accuracy tracker, alerting rules",
      "infra/ — Terraform/CDK for Redis/DynamoDB (feature store), S3 (model artifacts), SQS/Kafka (prediction events)"
    ],
    "patterns_to_follow": "Latency budget breakdown: 20ms feature assembly + 30ms inference + 20ms serialization/network = 70ms, leaving 30ms headroom for P99 variance. Use connection pooling for feature store. Model loaded once at startup, not per-request. Feature definitions as code — version-controlled, unit-tested, shared between training and serving as a Python package.",
    "pitfalls_to_avoid": [
      "DO NOT use a separate model serving framework (TF Serving, Seldon) for a single tree model — it adds latency and operational complexity with no benefit at this scale",
      "DO NOT compute features at inference time from raw data — pre-compute batch features; only assemble at serving time",
      "DO NOT skip the canary/shadow phase — deploying a new model to 100% traffic immediately is the #1 cause of ML production incidents",
      "DO NOT build a custom feature store platform — use a KV store with shared feature transform code; build the platform only when you have 10+ models",
      "DO NOT ignore training-serving skew — it is silent, cumulative, and the hardest ML bug to diagnose; invest in integration tests early",
      "DO NOT store model artifacts in the service container image — it couples deployment cadence to model release cadence; load from registry at startup"
    ]
  },

  "escalations": [],

  "confidence": {
    "level": 88,
    "high_confidence_areas": [
      "In-process tree model inference is the right call for 100ms P99 with tabular features — well-proven pattern",
      "Model Registry with pointer-swap rollback — standard, battle-tested approach",
      "Feature Store as shared kernel — directly addresses the highest-risk failure mode (training-serving skew)",
      "Phased implementation approach — serving path first, then training, then monitoring"
    ],
    "low_confidence_areas": [
      "Exact feature store technology choice (Redis vs DynamoDB) depends on existing infrastructure not specified",
      "Whether weekly retraining is frequent enough — depends on delivery pattern volatility which requires empirical measurement",
      "Automated rollback trigger thresholds — need baseline accuracy data to set meaningful thresholds"
    ],
    "assumptions": [
      "Tabular/structured input features (not images, text, or sequences) — tree models are appropriate",
      "Order volume is moderate (thousands to low millions of predictions/day) — single-digit serving instances sufficient",
      "Team has Python ML experience (XGBoost/LightGBM) and can operate basic cloud infrastructure (Redis, S3, container orchestration)",
      "Checkout latency budget of 100ms is end-to-end for the prediction call, not including upstream network from client"
    ]
  }
}

